  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(16) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And herein do I exercise myself . . .",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The “herein” seems equivalent to “in this belief.” Because he held that doctrine of a resurrection as a stern and solemn reality, the one law of his life was to keep his conscience clear from wilful sin. (See Note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 23:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) The words must have been almost as bitter to Felix as to Ananias; but he has, at all events, the decency to listen in silence.",
        "children": []
