  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Exercise myself (ἀσκῶ)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Originally, to work raw material, to form: hence, to practise, exercise, discipline; and so, in ecclesiastical language, to mortify the body. Of the kindred adjective ἀσκητικός our word ascetic is a transcript.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Void of offence (ἀπτόσκοπον)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Lit., without stumbling; unshaken. The word is used thus in a passive sense here, as in Philippians 1:10. In 1 Corinthians 10:32, it occurs in the active sense of giving offence to others, or causing them to stumble. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Lit., without stumbling; unshaken. The word is used thus in a passive sense here, as in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Philippians 1:10",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". In ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Corinthians 10:32",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", it occurs in the active sense of giving offence to others, or causing them to stumble. ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
